terror
of
the
mind.
It
was
unlikely
that
the
doctor
should
fear
death;
and
yet
that
was
what
Utterson
was
tempted
to
suspect.
“Yes,”
he
thought;
“he
is
a
doctor,
he
must
know
his
own
state
and
that
his
days
are
counted;
and
the
knowledge
is
more
than
he
can
bear.”
And
yet
when
Utterson
remarked
on
his
ill-looks,
it
was
with
an
air
of
great
firmness
that
Lanyon
declared
himself
a
doomed
man.
